<task id="AIPU2-070" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Create @spaarke/ai-widgets Package Scaffold</title>
    <phase>4A</phase>
    <tags>frontend, package, widgets</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>none</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    R2 introduces a new @spaarke/ai-widgets package that will house all WorkspaceWidgets and
    ContextWidgets for the three-pane shell. R1's output and source widgets lived directly in
    Spaarke.AI.Outputs with no clear separation from the output-registry. R2 separates the
    widget library into its own package so it can be versioned independently, consumed by both
    the SpaarkeAi solution and future host applications, and built without pulling in the entire
    AI context provider. Scaffold the package with correct build config, dependency declarations,
    and a barrel export before any widget code is written.
  </prompt>
  <role>Frontend developer with React 19, TypeScript, and npm package authoring experience.</role>
  <goal>
    The @spaarke/ai-widgets package builds successfully and exports its (initially empty) type
    barrel. It is correctly referenced by the SpaarkeAi solution. No widget implementations are
    required in this task.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-012-shared-components.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-021-fluent-design-system.md</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.AI.Outputs/package.json</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read ADR-012, ADR-021, and Spaarke.AI.Outputs/package.json to understand naming conventions, peer dependency requirements (Fluent v9, React version), and build tool patterns used in existing shared packages.</step>
    <step>Create directory src/client/shared/Spaarke.AI.Widgets/ with the following structure: package.json, tsconfig.json, vite.config.ts (or equivalent build config matching the pattern in Spaarke.AI.Outputs), src/index.ts (barrel export, initially empty).</step>
    <step>Set package name to @spaarke/ai-widgets in package.json; declare peerDependencies for react, react-dom, and @fluentui/react-components matching versions used in Spaarke.AI.Outputs.</step>
    <step>Add @spaarke/ui-components as a regular dependency (not peer) following ADR-012 shared component reuse requirement.</step>
    <step>Configure tsconfig.json to extend the root tsconfig and output declarations to dist/types/.</step>
    <step>Add the package to the SpaarkeAi solution's package.json as a workspace dependency so it can import from @spaarke/ai-widgets.</step>
    <step>Run the build (npm run build in the new package directory) and verify it completes without errors and produces a dist/ folder.</step>
    <step>Verify the SpaarkeAi solution resolves the @spaarke/ai-widgets import without errors (import {} from '@spaarke/ai-widgets' in a test file).</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>src/client/shared/Spaarke.AI.Widgets/ exists with package.json, tsconfig.json, build config, and src/index.ts.</criterion>
    <criterion>npm run build in Spaarke.AI.Widgets completes without errors and produces dist/.</criterion>
    <criterion>@spaarke/ai-widgets is resolvable from the SpaarkeAi solution (workspace dependency configured).</criterion>
    <criterion>Package follows ADR-012 (reuse @spaarke/ui-components) and ADR-021 (Fluent v9 peer dependency) constraints.</criterion>
    <criterion>No widget implementations are added — this task is scaffold only.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
